    <title>Combined summary - Secure Proof Of Stake implementation on Bitcoin</title>
    <updated>2023-06-13T20:07:54.847065+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2019-July/017121.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The email conversation discusses the implementation of Proof of Stake (PoS) in Bitcoin as an eco-friendly alternative to Proof of Work (PoW). The author suggests the use of PoS v3.0 with two additional improvements, hardcoded checkpoints and a block explorer or trusted source to download the hash of the current block height manually. However, ZmnSCPxj argues that under the trust-minimization and uncensorability requirements of Bitcoin, nothing is more efficient than PoW. Additionally, hardcoding checkpoints trusts the developers and is not acceptable for trust-minimization.The discussion covers the potential risks of PoS, including stake-grinding and the possibility of a single entity controlling &gt;51% of stakeable coins. The writer of the original email suggests that PoS could be 100% secure against all 51% history rewrite attacks with only two extra improvements required. The improvements include hardcoded checkpoints which protect the blockchain from a Long-Range attack. However, the proposal faces challenges related to trust-minimization and uncensorability requirements of Bitcoin.The email thread discusses various vulnerabilities and potential attacks on proof-of-work (PoW) and proof-of-stake (PoS) algorithms in cryptocurrencies. It explores the possibility of a 51% attack and how it can be avoided in PoS implementation. The use of short options as an economic attack is also discussed, along with the issue of non-linear stake weights that can lead to dominance by a single staker. The conversation highlights the need for careful consideration and analysis when implementing new protocols or making changes to existing ones, as adding more rules could potentially lead to worse attacks.Furthermore, the email conversation discusses energy waste in mining and the role of market forces in driving efficiency. The proposed solutions to the issues with PoS are not feasible as they make the protocol more complex and do not improve efficiency. The conversation also touches on the role of large stakeholders in coin dominance, the possibility of double spend attacks, and the use of dirty energy in Bitcoin mining. Additionally, there is a discussion about the potential implementation of PoS in Bitcoin Core, with some arguing that it introduces security risks.The email thread discusses the feasibility of a 51% attack under proof-of-work and proof-of-stake algorithms. The author argues that a 51% attack under proof-of-work is only possible if an entity has physical control of almost 50% or more of the globe due to energy availability being somewhat distributed over the world. In contrast, individual miners spread globally can join big mining pools, which could be hacked to participate in a 51% attack under proof-of-stake. The author suggests that changing the hashing algorithm is pointless in case of a 51% attack since control of energy sources matters more than hash power distribution.Lastly, the issue of energy waste in PoW is considered. The email thread concludes by stating that PoW is necessary, and fee-based confirmation is essential to overpower the censor, and the correct solution is to support the development and deployment of better poolminer protocols. Overall, the email thread provides insights into the ongoing debate about the best approach to cryptocurrency mining and the challenges associated with implementing new protocols.</summary>
